christopher krebs stepping out from his own shadow caesar as a man of letters stanford department of classics skip to navigation department of classics standford university logo header home people programs courses projects news events resources contact christopher krebs stepping out from his own shadow caesar as a man of letters thursday february 9 2012 5 15 7 15 pm main quad building 110 room 112 julius caesar was a highly esteemed man of letters whose fate it was to stand in the shadow cast by his performances as a general and historian this talk sheds new light on the bellum gallicum from which caesar emerges not only as well versed in lucretius de rerum natura and sisenna's histories but also as a linguist who readily employed or maybe coined rare words for the sake of precise expression christopher krebs is an associate professor of classics at harvard university who specializes in ancient historiography latin lexicography and the classical tradition he is the author of a most dangerous book tacitus's germania from the roman empire to the third reich login to post comments email stanford classics find us on facebook address & phone search upcoming events christopher krebs stepping out from his own shadow caesar as a man of letters 02 09 2012 felipe rojas gergas nannas semiramis picturing the past in roman asia minor 02 13 2012 alicia jimenez original copy imitation and colonialism in roman hispania 02 16 2012 see more recent news faculty grad student group awarded funding for shc research worshop 05 20 2011 stanford classics tops national research council rankings 09 28 2010 scit's production of aristophanes wasps in the spotlight 02 14 2011 see more news site info 2012 stanford university department of classics all rights reserved site design by chapter three login login with sunet speaker request webform for faculty stanford classics wikisite powered by drupal an open source content management system
